e between a beneficent environment and intensive cultivation ultimately became threatening to the soil and exploitative of the people who worked it.Invoking history, economics, sociology, agriculture, and environmental studies, Stoll traces the often tragic repercussions of fruit farming and shows how central this story is to the development of the industrial countryside in the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAgriculturexAspect économiquexCalifornie. 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectsxCalifornia. 0aAgriculturexEconomic aspectszCalifornia. 0aFruit tradexCalifornia. 0aFruit tradezCalifornia. 0aFruitxMarketingxCalifornia. 0aFruitzCaliforniaxMarketing. 0aFruitsxCommercexCalifornie. 0aFruitsxCommercialisationxCalifornie. 0aHorticulturexCalifornia. 0aHorticulturexCalifornie. 0aHorticulturezCalifornia. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press eBook Package Archivez978311063534840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520920200.jpg  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press eBook Package Archive  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles